res the multiple narratives of disaster--the official story of the crisis and its aftermath, as presented by the media and the state; the life stories of the individual victims, which both illuminate and challenge the ways we typically perceive natural disasters; and the scientific understandings of disaster and its management. Fatal Isolation is both a social history of risk and vulnerability in the urban landscape and a story of how a city copes with emerging threats and sudden, dramatic change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDisaster victimszFrancezParis. 0aHeat waves (Meteorology)zFrancezParisxHistoryy21st century. 0aNatural disasterszFrancezParisxHistoryy21st century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aheat wave, climate change, global warming, natural disaster, paris, france, death, suffering, isolation, aging, urban, risk, vulnerability, social marginalization, old age, epidemiology, space, place, mortality, nonfiction, history, science, sociology, cholera epidemic, architecture, city, medicine, public health, extreme weather, immigrants, refugees, urbanization, dehumanization, aged, environmental catastrophes, remembering, forgetting, memory, legacy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022625111040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226256436423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226256436/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles